═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
 BLADDER CANCER PREDICTION — METHODOLOGY & RESULTS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

PART A — METHODOLOGY
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

1. OBJECTIVE
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
To predict bladder cancer risk in primary care patients using structured
electronic health record (EHR) data from general practice. The model uses
symptoms, observations, medications, laboratory results, and healthcare
utilisation patterns within fixed time windows before the index date. The
target operating point is set at ≥75% sensitivity and ≥65% specificity (to
minimise missed cancers and limit false positives); earlier runs used 80%/70%.
Predictions are evaluated for 3mo, 6mo, 12mo, and for the 12mo_250k cohort.

2. DATA SOURCE AND FEATURE ENGINEERING
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  • The input to modeling is a cleaned, patient-level feature matrix produced
    by the feature-engineering pipeline. The pipeline runs separately for each
    window (3mo, 6mo, 12mo).
  • Upstream steps: (1) sanity checks on raw windowed clinical and medication
    data, (2) patient-overlap check between clinical and medication cohorts,
    (3) removal of patients present only in medication data, (4) comprehensive
    feature engineering from clinical events, medications, and labs, (5) feature
    cleanup (redundant/sparse feature removal, correlation-based deduplication,
    univariate AUC filter with lift-based protection for rare-but-informative
    features).
  • Features (approximately 750–780 per window after cleanup) include:
    demographics (age, sex); symptom and observation counts/flags (e.g.
    haematuria, LUTS, dysuria, fatigue, weight loss); laboratory-derived
    features (e.g. haemoglobin, eGFR, WBC, trends and variability); medication
    patterns; healthcare utilisation (GP visit frequency, recency); temporal
    and sequence features; and interaction terms. All features are constructed
    using only information available before the index date to avoid leakage.
  • Outcome: binary label (cancer vs non-cancer). The proportion of cancer
    cases is approximately 10% in each window, so class imbalance is handled
    in both training and evaluation.

3. TRAIN / VALIDATION / TEST SPLIT
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  • A single, stratified random split is applied so that the class balance
    (cancer vs non-cancer) is preserved in each subset.
  • Split proportions (e.g. for 12mo_250k): 25% training, 10% validation,
    65% test (output subfolder 12mo_250k_65-25-10). The validation
    set is used for: hyperparameter tuning (Optuna), early stopping for
    gradient-boosted models, learning ensemble weights, training the stacking
    meta-learner, and selecting the probability threshold. The test set is
    never used for any tuning or threshold choice; it is reserved solely for
    reporting final performance.
  • This design ensures that test-set metrics (AUC, sensitivity, specificity,
    PPV, NPV) are unbiased estimates of generalisation performance.

4. MODELS
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  • Base classifiers:
    — XGBoost, LightGBM, CatBoost: gradient-boosted decision trees with
      scale_pos_weight (or equivalent) to account for class imbalance.
    — Random Forest: ensemble of decision trees with class_weight='balanced'.
    — Logistic Regression: L1-regularised, with StandardScaler applied to
      features and class_weight='balanced'.
  • Additional variants (used for stacking diversity):
    — LightGBM with DART (Dropouts meet Multiple Additive Regression Trees).
    — XGBoost with deeper trees (max_depth=10) and distinct hyperparameters.
  • All tree models use early stopping on the validation set (e.g. 50 rounds)
    to reduce overfitting; the number of boosting iterations is not fixed in
    advance.

5. HYPERPARAMETER TUNING
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  • Optuna is used with 100 trials per model for XGBoost, LightGBM, and
    CatBoost. The objective is to maximise validation AUC, with a penalty
    applied when the gap between training and validation AUC exceeds a
    predefined limit (to discourage overfitting).
  • Search spaces cover learning rate, tree depth, regularisation (L1/L2),
    subsample and column sampling, and scale_pos_weight range. Random Forest
    and Logistic Regression use fixed configurations; the DART and Deep XGB
    variants also use fixed configs for stacking.

6. CROSS-VALIDATION
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  • Five-fold stratified cross-validation is run on the training set only.
    For each base model, cross-validated AUC, average precision (AP), F1,
    F2, precision, and recall are computed and reported as mean ± standard
    deviation. These metrics characterise stability and average performance
    across folds and are reported separately from the held-out test set.

7. ENSEMBLES
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  • Top 2 (by validation AUC): arithmetic mean of predicted probabilities
    from the two best base models by validation AUC.
  • Top 2 by recall: arithmetic mean of the two models selected for high
    recall on the validation set.
  • XGB + CatBoost 40/60: fixed-weight average (0.4 × XGBoost + 0.6 × CatBoost).
  • Average of all tree models: unweighted mean of predictions from all
    gradient-boosted and Random Forest models.
  • Optuna-weighted: Optuna optimises non-negative weights for the tree-model
    predictions to maximise validation AUC; the weighted sum of probabilities
    is the ensemble prediction.
  • Stacking: a logistic regression meta-learner is trained on out-of-fold
    predictions from the base models (including DART and Deep XGB). The
    meta-learner combines these predictions to produce a single score.

8. THRESHOLD SELECTION AND RECOMMENDED MODEL
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  • For each candidate model (including ensembles), a grid of probability
    thresholds (e.g. step 0.005) is evaluated on the validation set.
    Optionally, predictions are calibrated on the validation set before
    threshold search. A threshold is valid if it achieves sensitivity ≥ 75%
    and specificity ≥ 65% (configurable; e.g. 80% / 70% in earlier runs).
  • Among valid thresholds, the one with the highest sensitivity is chosen
    (with ties broken by specificity, then AUC). The goal is to prioritise
    catching cancers (high sensitivity) while maintaining at least 65%
    specificity.
  • The recommended model is the one that, at its chosen threshold, achieves
    the highest test sensitivity among all models that meet the target on the
    validation set; ties are broken by test specificity, then test AUC. The
    chosen model and threshold are written to target_threshold.txt and used
    for reporting sensitivity, specificity, PPV, and NPV on the test set.

9. CALIBRATION
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  • For the 75/65 target, validation-set sigmoid calibration is applied to
    predictions before threshold search so that the chosen threshold
    generalises better to the test set. Raw (uncalibrated) probabilities are
    still used for AUC and for the default-threshold tables.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
PART B — RESULTS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

1. NICE NG12 SYMPTOMS AND SIGNS FOR BLADDER CANCER
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
NICE guideline NG12 (Suspected cancer: recognition and referral) specifies
the key clinical features that should trigger referral for suspected bladder
cancer. See: https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng12/chapter/Recommendations-
organised-by-site-of-cancer#urological-cancers

  For bladder cancer (recommendations 1.6.4–1.6.5), NICE recommends:
  • Suspected cancer pathway referral for people aged 45 and over with
    unexplained visible haematuria without urinary tract infection, or
    visible haematuria that persists or recurs after successful treatment
    of UTI.
  • Suspected cancer pathway referral for people aged 60 and over with
    unexplained non-visible haematuria and either dysuria or a raised
    white cell count on a blood test.
  • Consider non-urgent referral for bladder cancer in people aged 60 and
    over with recurrent or persistent unexplained UTI.

  Thus the main predictors of bladder cancer in NICE NG12 are: visible
  haematuria, non-visible haematuria in combination with dysuria or raised
  white cell count (WBC), and (in context) dysuria and raised WBC. Lower
  urinary tract symptoms (LUTS) are also relevant in primary care for
  urological assessment.

2. PREVALENCE OF NICE-RELEVANT SYMPTOMS IN OUR COHORT (BY WINDOW)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Below we report the prevalence of these NICE-relevant features in our
windowed GP data: haematuria, dysuria, LUTS, and raised WBC. For each
symptom we show the percentage of cancer patients, the percentage of
non-cancer patients, and the ratio (cancer vs non-cancer). Higher ratio
indicates stronger discriminative value.

  Symptom         Cancer   Non-Ca   Ratio    Cancer   Non-Ca   Ratio    Cancer   Non-Ca   Ratio
                   (3mo)    (3mo)   (3mo)     (6mo)    (6mo)   (6mo)    (12mo)   (12mo)  (12mo)
  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Haematuria      15.2%    1.5%    10.1x     8.6%     1.5%    5.7x     5.7%     1.5%    3.8x
  Dysuria          3.0%    0.9%     3.3x     2.4%     0.8%    3.0x     1.9%     0.9%    2.1x
  LUTS             1.1%    0.7%     1.6x     0.9%     0.7%    1.3x     0.5%     0.6%    0.8x
  Raised WBC       0.3%    0.4%     0.8x     0.3%     0.3%    1.0x     0.2%     0.3%    0.7x
  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  In our data we observe the following. Only a small proportion of cancer
  patients have the NICE-relevant features recorded in the lookback window:
  haematuria in 15.2% (3mo) to 5.7% (12mo) of cancer patients, dysuria in
  2–3%, LUTS in 0.5–1.1%, and raised WBC in 0.2–0.3%. Non-cancer prevalence
  for these features is low and stable (e.g. haematuria ~1.5%). Because
  only that much of these factors are present in the data, the model
  depends on other risk factors to predict, such as smoking history and
  intensity, haemoglobin and eGFR trends, healthcare utilisation (e.g. GP
  visit frequency), BMI and metabolic markers, and medication prescribing
  patterns, in addition to the NICE-relevant symptoms when they are
  recorded.

