4. OVERALL MODEL PERFORMANCE AND RELATED FINDINGS
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  • All three windows meet the target operating point (≥80% sensitivity,
    ≥70% specificity) on the held-out test set. Sensitivity is highest at
    3mo (85.9%) and slightly lower at 12mo (80.1%); specificity increases
    with window length (69.4% at 3mo to 71.2% at 12mo).
  • Test AUC is strong in every window (0.847–0.880). The drop from 3mo to
    12mo is modest (0.034), so the model retains most of its discriminative
    ability when using a longer lookback. Best AUC is achieved by
    ensembles (Stacking or Optuna-weighted depending on window).
  • PPV is ~23–24% in all windows, in line with ~10% cancer prevalence in
    the cohort. NPV is high (97%+), so a negative score is a useful rule-out.
  • In our data, recorded urinary symptoms (haematuria, dysuria, LUTS) and
    raised WBC are present in only a small proportion of cancer patients
    in each window; the model therefore relies heavily on other predictors
    (e.g. smoking, Hb/eGFR trends, healthcare use, BMI, medications) to
    achieve the reported performance.
  • Shorter windows (3mo) capture more symptom-rich periods and yield
    higher sensitivity; longer windows (12mo) rely more on risk factors
    and lab trends, with a small cost in AUC and sensitivity.
  • Choice of window can be guided by intended use: 12mo for earlier risk
    flagging; 3mo when prioritising maximum sensitivity closer to diagnosis.

